In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires:
"taxable income" means the gross income of a person for a year of assessment after deducting all
allowable expenses and reliefs as provided under this Act;
"company" means a body corporate established under the laws of Nigeria or any other jurisdiction,
including corporations, partnerships, and limited liability companies;
"individual" means a natural person who is resident in Nigeria or derives income from Nigeria,
subject to personal income taxation under this Act;
"digital asset" means any digital representation of value or contractual rights that can be
transferred, stored, or traded electronically, including but not limited to cryptocurrencies, virtual
currencies, non-fungible tokens (NFTs), and other blockchain-based assets;
"virtual asset" has the same meaning as digital asset;

The taxable income of a company for a year of assessment shall consist of:
(a) profits from trade, business, profession, or vocation;
(b) gains from the disposal of assets;
(c) dividends, interests, royalties, and rents;
(d) income from digital assets and virtual assets;
(e) any other income derived from sources within or outside Nigeria. For the purposes of computing taxable income, a company may deduct all expenses wholly,
exclusively, and necessarily incurred in the production of income, including depreciation
allowances, pension contributions, and bad debts written off.

The taxable income of an individual for a year of assessment shall include:
(a) emoluments from employment including salaries, wages, bonuses, and allowances;
(b) income from business or professional practice;
(c) gains from the disposal of assets;
(d) investment income including dividends, interests, and rents;
(e) income from digital and virtual assets;
(f) any other income from sources within or outside Nigeria. An individual shall be entitled to deductions including consolidated relief allowance calculated as
1% of gross income or I200,000 (whichever is higher) plus 20% of gross income.

The Federal Inland Revenue Service (FIRS) is hereby replaced by the Nigeria Revenue Service
(NRS) which shall be the primary tax authority responsible for the administration and collection of
taxes under this Act. The NRS shall:
(a) assess, collect, and account for all federal taxes;
(b) enforce compliance with tax laws;
(c) maintain a central tax database;
(d) coordinate with state revenue services. The NRS shall operate under the supervision of the Joint Revenue Board established under the
Joint Revenue Board Establishment Act 2024.

Value Added Tax (VAT) shall be charged at the rate of 7.5% on the supply of all goods and services
in Nigeria, except those specifically exempted under Schedule 2 of this Act. The following persons shall register for VAT and charge VAT on their supplies:
(a) any person whose annual turnover exceeds I25,000,000;
(b) any person who imports goods or services into Nigeria;
(c) any person who makes taxable supplies regardless of turnover, at their option.

It is empowered to promote consistency, resolve jurisdictional overlaps, and provide
strategic guidance on fiscal matters that cut across multiple tiers of government. Key Functions and Powers
The JRB is tasked with a comprehensive range of responsibilities, including:
â€¢ Coordinating the integration and maintenance of a national taxpayer identification database
(TINs);
â€¢ Advising on double taxation matters and promoting the harmonisation of tax rates and practices
across Nigeria;
â€¢ Publishing tax expenditure reports, including analyses of waivers, exemptions, and incentives
issued by all levels of government;
â€¢ Facilitating tax policy reform, capacity building, and the accreditation of tax agents;
â€¢ Undertaking taxpayer behaviour research, compliance audits, and policy impact assessments.

Claims must be made within
six years and must be accompanied by proper documentation. Audit, Enforcement and Penalties
Tax authorities are granted broad investigative powers. These include the right to:
â€¢ Call for documents and inspect books and records, both physical and electronic;
â€¢ Enter premises (with judicial warrant for private residences);
â€¢ Remove or copy evidence;


â€¢ Appoint third-party collection agents where necessary;
â€¢ Distrain (seize and sell assets) of defaulting taxpayers, with court approval required for immovable
property. Penalties are significantly enhanced. Late filing attracts a I100,000 penalty in the first month and
I50,000 for each subsequent month, while interest accrues at the Central Bank's Monetary Policy
Rate (or SOFR for foreign-denominated taxes).

Mandate and Powers
The Act mandates the NRS to:
â€¢ Administer and enforce all federal tax laws and collect revenues accruing to the Federation;
â€¢ Assess and account for taxes, levies, and charges imposed by federal legislation;
â€¢ Enforce compliance, including powers to trace, freeze, seize, or confiscate proceeds of tax fraud
or evasion;
â€¢ Collaborate with other national and international bodies for the exchange of tax information;
â€¢ Maintain a centralised taxpayer database and issue Taxpayer Identification Numbers (TINs) in
collaboration with state tax authorities and the Joint Revenue Board. The NRS is also empowered to assist subnational governments (State, FCT, and Local
Government) in tax administration, when requested or where inter-agency collaboration is required
by law.

The Board includes representatives from Nigeria's six geopolitical zones
and relevant federal agencies and ministries, ensuring national balance and inter-ministerial
coordination. Among other responsibilities, the Board is tasked with:
â€¢ Approving strategic plans and performance frameworks;
â€¢ Overseeing financial and operational policies;
â€¢ Employing and managing staff, and setting remuneration;
â€¢ Monitoring tax policy implementation and recommending reforms where needed. Operational Funding and Enforcement


The NRS is authorised to fund its operations through a 4% cost-of-collection allocation from
non-petroleum tax revenues (i.e., excluding petroleum royalties). It may also receive grants, gifts,
and returns from investments, subject to appropriate approvals.
